      "document_id": "demo_lesson_c1a06efdd8",
      "document_title": "DEMO LESSON",
      "chunk_text": "Photosynthesis is the process plants use to convert light energy into chemical energy.\nThis process allows plants to produce glucose, which stores energy that supports growth and survival.\nPhotosynthesis mainly takes place in the chloroplasts of plant cells.\nChlorophyll, the green pigment inside chloroplasts, helps capture sunlight from the environment.\nWater absorbed by the roots and carbon dioxide from the air are key inputs used during photosynthesis.\nUsing these inputs and sunlight, plants produce glucose and release oxygen as an output.\nPhotosynthesis is important because it supports plant life, contributes oxygen to the atmosphere, and helps sustain food chains.",
      "chunk_index": 0,
      "section_heading": "DEMO LESSON",
